Note:
R Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the R translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    R source
      -> r_lexer    (tokenize: names, keywords, numbers, strings, operators,
                     the R-only %%/%/%/^ operators, <-/=/<<- assignment, $/[[/[/::,
                     |> pipe, c(...)/list(...))
      -> r_parser   (build the locked 72-byte R AST: function defs with defaults,
                     if/else, for, assignments, calls with named args, vectors,
                     member/slot/namespace access, indexing)
      -> r_to_hir   (lower the R AST to the canonical hir_nodes producer model,
                     tagging every R-only spelling with an "r_*" metadata key)
      -> hir_to_r   (emit HIR back to valid R text, recovering each R spelling)
      -> re-lex / re-parse / re-to_hir of the emitted text
      -> structural HIR equality on the key constructs (CONTENT, not presence)

The probe feeds a representative R program that exercises every major construct the
task requires:

  - >= 6 function definitions          (square/cube/add/scale/describe/combine <- function ...)
  - an assignment with <-              (every function binding plus result <- ...)
  - a default-argument parameter       (function(x, y = 1) ...)
  - an if/else                         (if (n > 10) ... else ...)
  - a for-loop                         (for (i in seq) ...)
  - a c(...) vector with elements      (nums <- c(1, 2, 3, 4))
  - $ and [[ ]] indexing               (df$col ; lst[[1]])
  - a named call argument              (scale(nums, factor = 2))

It lowers the source to HIR1, asserts the CONTENT of each construct (function names,
the assignment operator token, the default-arg parameter, the if/else branches, the
for-loop variable, the vector's element count, the $/[[ access kinds, the named
argument name), emits HIR1 back to R text, re-runs the whole pipeline on the emitted
text to HIR2, and asserts HIR2 is STRUCTURALLY EQUAL to HIR1 on those same key
constructs. Structural equality (node-kind tags plus identifying payloads) is the
correct semantic-equivalence check because the emitter re-indents and normalises
whitespace while the meaning is identical.

The R HIR node model is the canonical hir_nodes producer surface: every node is an
int-tagged record read via hir_node_type (the kind) and the hir_get_* accessors
(structural fields). R function definitions are bound through an assignment whose
right-hand side is the HIR function node, so the probe walks expression statements
to their inner assignments to reach the functions.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/r/r_parser.runa" as RParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/r/r_to_hir.runa" as RFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/r/hir_to_r.runa" as RBackend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each round of the probe runs the identical front-of-pipeline (parse -> to_hir).
Factoring it into one helper keeps the two pipeline runs (original source and
emitted text) behaviourally identical so any structural divergence is attributable
to the emitter, not to a difference in how the inputs were driven.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Drives parse_r_source to the R AST_PROGRAM root, then lowers it via
translate_r_to_hir and returns the HIR module. Returns 0 if any stage yields 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ast be proc parse_r_source from RParser with source
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let hir be proc translate_r_to_hir from RFrontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The R frontend wraps top-level statements in expression statements and binds
functions through assignment. R parses every assignment operator (<-, =, <<-, ->,
->>) as a binary operator carrying the operator token in "r_op_token", so an
assignment lowers to a HIR_BINARY_EXPR tagged with the assignment token (8020 for
<-, 8024 for =, etc.). This helper returns the inner binary-assignment expression of
a declaration when that declaration is an expression statement wrapping a binary
expression whose r_op_token is one of the assignment tokens; 0 otherwise. It is the
shared step every function/vector lookup uses to reach the assigned value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "decl_assign" takes decl as Integer returns Integer:
    If decl is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let decl_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
    If decl_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPR_STMT:
        Let inner be proc hir_get_expression_statement_expr from HIR with decl
        Let is_assign be proc is_assignment_binary with inner
        If is_assign is equal to 1:
            Return inner
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns 1 when a node is an assignment expressed as a binary operator: a
HIR_BINARY_EXPR whose "r_op_token" is one of R's assignment tokens (8020 <-, 8021
<<-, 8022 ->, 8023 ->>, 8024 =). This is the canonical recogniser for R assignments,
which the parser models as binary operators rather than dedicated assignment nodes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_assignment_binary" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with node
    If kind is not equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPR:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let token be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "r_op_token"
    If token is equal to 8020:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token is equal to 8021:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token is equal to 8022:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token is equal to 8023:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token is equal to 8024:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the assignment target (left-hand side) of a binary-assignment node via
hir_get_binary_left, since R assignments are binary expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assign_lhs" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc hir_get_binary_left from HIR with node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the assigned value (right-hand side) of a binary-assignment node via
hir_get_binary_right, since R assignments are binary expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assign_rhs" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc hir_get_binary_right from HIR with node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts the function definitions in the module. Each function is the right-hand side
of a top-level assignment (name <- function(...){...}). Linear-scanning the
declarations and counting assignments whose RHS is a HIR_FUNCTION proves >= 6
functions survive both lowering and round-trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "count_functions" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let found be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let assign be proc decl_assign with decl
        If assign is not equal to 0:
            Let rhs be proc assign_rhs with assign
            Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
            If rhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_FUNCTION:
                Set found to found plus 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return found
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the HIR function node bound to a given name, located by scanning the
top-level assignments for one whose left-hand identifier matches the requested name
and whose right-hand side is a function. This lets the probe assert a SPECIFIC
function (by name) survives, not merely that some function exists.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_function_named" takes module as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let assign be proc decl_assign with decl
        If assign is not equal to 0:
            Let lhs be proc assign_lhs with assign
            Let lhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with lhs
            If lhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
                Let lhs_name be proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with lhs
                Let name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with lhs_name, name
                If name_ok is equal to 1:
                    Let rhs be proc assign_rhs with assign
                    Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
                    If rhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_FUNCTION:
                        Return rhs
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locates the first top-level declaration of a given HIR kind (e.g. HIR_IF, HIR_FOR_IN)
by linear scan, robust to statement reordering. Used to reach the if/else and the
for-loop directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_decl" takes module as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let decl_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
        If decl_kind is equal to kind:
            Return decl
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the right-hand side of the first top-level assignment whose RHS is a member
expression carrying the given tag value ("r_s4_slot" present, or a $ access which has
no tag). When tag is the empty string the helper matches a plain $ member access
(no namespace and no slot tag); otherwise it matches a member expression whose tag
key is set to "true". This reaches the $ access and (separately) any tagged access.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_assign_rhs_member" takes module as Integer, tag as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let assign be proc decl_assign with decl
        If assign is not equal to 0:
            Let rhs be proc assign_rhs with assign
            Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
            If rhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
                Let tag_val be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with rhs, tag
                Let has_tag be proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_val, "true"
                If has_tag is equal to 1:
                    Return rhs
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the c(...) vector bound to a variable. In R, c(1, 2, 3, 4) is a call to the
built-in "c" function (the locked R parser models it as a NODE_CALL), so it lowers to
a HIR_CALL_EXPR whose callee is the identifier "c". This helper scans the top-level
assignments for the first whose RHS is a call to "c" and returns that call, so the
probe can assert the vector's element count (its positional argument count) survives.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_c_call" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let assign be proc decl_assign with decl
        If assign is not equal to 0:
            Let rhs be proc assign_rhs with assign
            Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
            If rhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
                Let callee be proc hir_get_call_callee from HIR with rhs
                Let callee_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with callee
                If callee_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
                    Let callee_name be proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with callee
                    Let is_c be proc string_equals from StringCore with callee_name, "c"
                    If is_c is equal to 1:
                        Return rhs
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the number of elements in a c(...) vector call: its positional-argument count.
Proves the vector's element content survives lowering and round-trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "c_call_element_count" takes call_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If call_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let args be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with call_node
    If args is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc list_length from List with args
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the right-hand side of the first top-level assignment whose RHS is an index
expression carrying the given tag value ("r_extract" for [[ ]]). This reaches the
double-bracket element extraction bound to a variable.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_assign_rhs_index" takes module as Integer, tag as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let assign be proc decl_assign with decl
        If assign is not equal to 0:
            Let rhs be proc assign_rhs with assign
            Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
            If rhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_INDEX_EXPR:
                Let tag_val be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with rhs, tag
                Let has_tag be proc string_equals from StringCore with tag_val, "true"
                If has_tag is equal to 1:
                    Return rhs
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locates the call carrying a named argument (e.g. scale(nums, factor = 2)). It is the
RHS of a top-level assignment, a HIR_CALL_EXPR. R parses a named argument as a binary
"=" expression (token 8024) whose left operand is the parameter-name identifier, so
the helper returns the first positional argument that is such a binary "=" node. The
caller reads the argument name via named_argument_name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_named_argument" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let assign be proc decl_assign with decl
        If assign is not equal to 0:
            Let rhs be proc assign_rhs with assign
            Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
            If rhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
                Let args be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with rhs
                If args is not equal to 0:
                    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args
                    Let j be 0
                    While j is less than arg_count:
                        Let arg be proc list_get from List with args, j
                        Let is_named be proc is_named_argument with arg
                        If is_named is equal to 1:
                            Return arg
                        End If
                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns 1 when a call argument is a named argument: a HIR_BINARY_EXPR carrying the R
"=" token (8024). R's `name = value` call argument is parsed as an "=" binary, so this
recogniser identifies it structurally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_named_argument" takes arg as Integer returns Integer:
    If arg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with arg
    If kind is not equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPR:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let token be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with arg, "r_op_token"
    If token is equal to 8024:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the parameter-name string of a named call argument: the left operand of the
"=" binary is the name identifier, so this reads hir_get_binary_left and then the
identifier's name. Proves the named argument's NAME (content) round-trips.
@End Reasoning
Process called "named_argument_name" takes arg as Integer returns Integer:
    If arg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let left be proc hir_get_binary_left from HIR with arg
    Let left_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with left
    If left_kind is not equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two R programs are structurally equal on a construct when both HIR projections expose
the same node-kind tag. Comparing kinds (and, for named constructs, the identifying
payload) rather than byte text is whitespace-insensitive, proving round-trip fidelity
without being defeated by the emitter's re-indenting.
@End Reasoning
Process called "same_kind" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ka be proc hir_node_type from HIR with a
    Let kb be proc hir_node_type from HIR with b
    If ka is equal to kb:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts the parameters carried by a HIR function. hir_get_parameters returns the
callable's collection handle (the node itself); the ordered parameter List is then
resolved via hir_get_parameter_list. Used to confirm the default-arg function keeps
both of its parameters across the round-trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "function_param_count" takes func_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If func_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let handle be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with func_node
    Let params be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with handle
    If params is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc list_length from List with params
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns 1 when the function's parameter at the given index carries a default value
(tagged "r_has_default"). hir_get_parameters returns the handle, resolved to the List
via hir_get_parameter_list. Proves the default-argument parameter round-trips with its
default intact rather than collapsing to a plain parameter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "param_has_default" takes func_node as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If func_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let handle be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with func_node
    Let params be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with handle
    If params is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with params
    If index is greater than or equal to count:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let param be proc list_get from List with params, index
    Let tag be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with param, "r_has_default"
    Return proc string_equals from StringCore with tag, "true"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "R translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative R program. Newlines separate the statements. It defines six
    functions (one with a default argument and an if/else body and a for-loop),
    binds a c(...) vector, performs $ and [[ ]] access, and makes a call with a
    named argument.
    :End Note
    Let source be "square <- function(x) x * x\ncube <- function(x) x * x * x\nadd <- function(a, b) a + b\nscale <- function(v, factor = 1) v * factor\ndescribe <- function(n) {\nif (n > 10) {\nresult <- \"big\"\n} else {\nresult <- \"small\"\n}\nresult\n}\ncombine <- function(items) {\ntotal <- 0\nfor (i in items) {\ntotal <- total + i\n}\ntotal\n}\nnums <- c(1, 2, 3, 4)\nscaled <- scale(nums, factor = 2)\ncolumn <- df$value\nfirst <- lst[[1]]\n"

    Note: --- Stage 0-2: source -> HIR1 (parse, lower) ---
    Let ast be proc parse_r_source from RParser with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser produced R AST", ast

    Let hir1 be proc translate_r_to_hir from RFrontend with ast
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "frontend produced HIR module", hir1

    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR module has declarations", declarations
    Let decl_count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "module has several top-level declarations", decl_count, 6

    Note: --- >= 6 function definitions, located by name (CONTENT) ---
    Let func_total be proc count_functions with hir1
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "module defines at least 6 functions", func_total, 6

    Let f_square be proc find_function_named with hir1, "square"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function 'square' present", f_square
    Let f_cube be proc find_function_named with hir1, "cube"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function 'cube' present", f_cube
    Let f_add be proc find_function_named with hir1, "add"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function 'add' present", f_add
    Let f_scale be proc find_function_named with hir1, "scale"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function 'scale' present", f_scale
    Let f_describe be proc find_function_named with hir1, "describe"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function 'describe' present", f_describe
    Let f_combine be proc find_function_named with hir1, "combine"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function 'combine' present", f_combine

    Note: --- assignment with <- : an assign expr carrying the <- token (8020) ---
    Let nums_assign be 0
    Let scan_count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let s be 0
    While s is less than scan_count:
        Let d be proc list_get from List with declarations, s
        Let a be proc decl_assign with d
        If a is not equal to 0:
            If nums_assign is equal to 0:
                Set nums_assign to a
            End If
        End If
        Set s to s plus 1
    End While
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "an assignment statement present", nums_assign
    Let assign_token be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with nums_assign, "r_op_token"
    Let token_is_left be 0
    If assign_token is equal to 8020:
        Set token_is_left to 1
    End If
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "assignment uses the <- operator (token 8020)", token_is_left, 1

    Note: --- default-argument parameter: scale has 2 params, param 1 has a default ---
    Let scale_param_count be proc function_param_count with f_scale
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "'scale' has 2 parameters", scale_param_count, 2
    Let scale_has_default be proc param_has_default with f_scale, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "'scale' parameter 'factor' has a default", scale_has_default, 1

    Note: --- if/else: located by kind inside 'describe' body; here as a top-level
    Note: form it is reached through the function body, so we assert the function
    Note: body contains an if with both branches. ---
    Let describe_body be proc hir_get_function_body from HIR with f_describe
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "'describe' has a body", describe_body
    Let if_node be proc first_if_in_block with describe_body
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if statement present in 'describe'", if_node
    Let if_cond be proc hir_get_if_condition from HIR with if_node
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if statement has a condition", if_cond
    Let if_else be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with if_node
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if statement has an else branch", if_else

    Note: --- for-loop: inside 'combine' body, a for-in with the loop variable 'i' ---
    Let combine_body be proc hir_get_function_body from HIR with f_combine
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "'combine' has a body", combine_body
    Let for_node be proc first_for_in_block with combine_body
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "for-loop present in 'combine'", for_node
    Let for_var be proc hir_get_for_in_variable from HIR with for_node
    Let for_var_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with for_var, "i"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "for-loop variable is 'i'", for_var_ok, 1

    Note: --- c(...) vector: a list literal RHS tagged r_vector with 4 elements ---
    Let vector_node be proc find_c_call with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "c(...) vector present", vector_node
    Let vector_count be proc c_call_element_count with vector_node
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "c() vector has 4 elements", vector_count, 4

    Note: --- $ access: a member expr RHS with no namespace/slot tag ---
    Let dollar_node be proc find_plain_member with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "$ member access present", dollar_node
    Let dollar_name be proc hir_get_member_name from HIR with dollar_node
    Let dollar_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with dollar_name, "value"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "$ access reads member 'value'", dollar_name_ok, 1

    Note: --- [[ ]] extraction: an index expr RHS tagged r_extract ---
    Let extract_node be proc find_assign_rhs_index with hir1, "r_extract"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "[[ ]] extraction present", extract_node

    Note: --- named call argument: scale(nums, factor = 2) ---
    Let named_arg be proc find_named_argument with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "named call argument present", named_arg
    Let named_arg_name be proc named_argument_name with named_arg
    Let named_arg_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with named_arg_name, "factor"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "named argument is 'factor'", named_arg_ok, 1

    Note: --- Stage 3: HIR -> R text ---
    Let emitted be proc hir_to_r from RBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced R text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted R is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 4: re-run the pipeline on the emitted text -> HIR2 ---
    Let hir2 be proc source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted R produced HIR", hir2
    Let decls2 be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir2
    Let decl2_count be proc list_length from List with decls2
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip module has declarations", decl2_count, 6

    Note: --- Stage 5: structural equality on the key constructs (CONTENT) ---
    Let func2_total be proc count_functions with hir2
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves at least 6 functions", func2_total, 6

    Let f_scale2 be proc find_function_named with hir2, "scale"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function 'scale'", f_scale2
    Let scale2_param_count be proc function_param_count with f_scale2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 'scale' 2 parameters", scale2_param_count, 2
    Let scale2_has_default be proc param_has_default with f_scale2, 1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 'factor' default", scale2_has_default, 1

    Let f_describe2 be proc find_function_named with hir2, "describe"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function 'describe'", f_describe2
    Let describe2_body be proc hir_get_function_body from HIR with f_describe2
    Let if2 be proc first_if_in_block with describe2_body
    Let if_kind_ok be proc same_kind with if_node, if2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves the if statement", if_kind_ok, 1
    Let if2_else be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with if2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves the else branch", if2_else

    Let f_combine2 be proc find_function_named with hir2, "combine"
    Let combine2_body be proc hir_get_function_body from HIR with f_combine2
    Let for2 be proc first_for_in_block with combine2_body
    Let for_kind_ok be proc same_kind with for_node, for2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves the for-loop", for_kind_ok, 1
    Let for2_var be proc hir_get_for_in_variable from HIR with for2
    Let for2_var_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with for2_var, "i"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves for-loop variable 'i'", for2_var_ok, 1

    Let vector2 be proc find_c_call with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves the c() vector", vector2
    Let vector2_count be proc c_call_element_count with vector2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 4 vector elements", vector2_count, 4

    Let dollar2 be proc find_plain_member with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves $ access", dollar2
    Let dollar2_name be proc hir_get_member_name from HIR with dollar2
    Let dollar2_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with dollar2_name, "value"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves $ member 'value'", dollar2_name_ok, 1

    Let extract2 be proc find_assign_rhs_index with hir2, "r_extract"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves [[ ]] extraction", extract2

    Let named_arg2 be proc find_named_argument with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves named argument", named_arg2
    Let named_arg2_name be proc named_argument_name with named_arg2
    Let named_arg2_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with named_arg2_name, "factor"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves named argument 'factor'", named_arg2_ok, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the first if statement inside a function body block. R function bodies are
HIR blocks; the if (and its else) sit as block statements, so this scans the block's
statement list for the first HIR_IF and returns it. A single-statement body that is
itself an if is handled by also testing the body node directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "first_if_in_block" takes body as Integer returns Integer:
    If body is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let body_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with body
    If body_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
        Return body
    End If
    If body_kind is not equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let statements be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with body
    If statements is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with statements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let stmt be proc list_get from List with statements, i
        Let stmt_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with stmt
        If stmt_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
            Return stmt
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the first for-in loop inside a function body block, mirroring first_if_in_block.
Scans the block's statement list for the first HIR_FOR_IN.
@End Reasoning
Process called "first_for_in_block" takes body as Integer returns Integer:
    If body is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let body_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with body
    If body_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR_IN:
        Return body
    End If
    If body_kind is not equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let statements be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with body
    If statements is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with statements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let stmt be proc list_get from List with statements, i
        Let stmt_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with stmt
        If stmt_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR_IN:
            Return stmt
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the right-hand side of the first top-level assignment whose RHS is a plain $
member access: a HIR_MEMBER_EXPR with neither the "r_namespace" nor the "r_s4_slot"
tag set. This isolates the df$value access from any @ slot or :: namespace member
expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_plain_member" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let assign be proc decl_assign with decl
        If assign is not equal to 0:
            Let rhs be proc assign_rhs with assign
            Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
            If rhs_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
                Let ns be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with rhs, "r_namespace"
                Let slot be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with rhs, "r_s4_slot"
                Let is_ns be proc string_equals from StringCore with ns, "true"
                Let is_slot be proc string_equals from StringCore with slot, "true"
                If is_ns is equal to 0:
                    If is_slot is equal to 0:
                        Return rhs
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process
